Noah Levitt wrote:
&gt; (commented on the jira issue) I don&#39;t think the problem here is the mask 
&gt; (which looks like 8 bits to me). What&#39;s happening with, for example, the 
&gt; euro character (€) on a windows-1252 encoded page (0x80) is that when 
&gt; you cast it to char it takes the numeric value as a unicode codepoint. 
&gt; 0x80 is a control character in unicode. The correct conversion would be 
&gt; to 0x20ac, which can be obtained with new String(byte[] {0x80}, 
&gt; &quot;windows-1252&quot;), or maybe more efficiently with a CharsetDecoder.

I think there are two problems: not considering the encoding in use, and 
further masking the return value to 8 bits, when a char would normally 
include values outside an 8-bit range. Either alone is enough so that 
ByteReplayCharSequence.charAt() will give a wrong result for certain 
characters.

Yes, the fix is to apply the appropriate charset decoding to the bytes, 
and completely eliminate the masking on that result.

However, we&#39;re unlikely to want to do the decoding a byte at a time in 
charAt() -- the Java decoders, even for single-byte encodings, don&#39;t 
offer operations on single bytes, only ByteBuffers into CharBuffers. So 
some other refactoring to do decoding in larger batches will likely be 
worthwhile.

- Gordon @ IA

&gt; Noah
&gt; 
&gt; Gordon Mohr wrote:
&gt;&gt; Jean-Noël Rivasseau wrote:
&gt;&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; Hello.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; My problem was that I had a page that was actually encoded in
&gt;&gt;&gt; windows-1252 cp, but advertised itself as a ISO-8859-1 page (although
&gt;&gt;&gt; it did this only in the HTML content of the page, not on the
&gt;&gt;&gt; appropriate place - the HTTP headers, but anyway as you pointed
&gt;&gt;&gt; Heritrix probably picked ISO-8859-1 as default).
&gt;&gt;&gt;     
&gt;&gt; Was there any hint or declaration that windows-1252 was the proper 
&gt;&gt; encoding, or would it have to be deduced by statistical guesswork from 
&gt;&gt; that page if you didn&#39;t already know the expected encoding? (Is this a 
&gt;&gt; public URL you can share?)
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; In my Processor I manually forced the encoding like this (uri is a
&gt;&gt;&gt; ProcessorURI):
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; uri.getRecorder().setCharacterEncoding(&quot;windows-1252&quot;);
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; However, although my JVM perfectly supports this encoding (I checked),
&gt;&gt;&gt; things were still not working, specifically, the Euro currency
&gt;&gt;&gt; character/symbol, coded by the byte 80 in hex in Windows-1252,
&gt;&gt;&gt; appeared garbled when I converted the uri to a String via
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; String content = uri.getRecorder().getReplayCharSequence().toString();
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; I looked at the source and found this strange comment in the
&gt;&gt;&gt; getReplayCharSequence() of RecordingOutputStream :
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; // TODO: take into account single-byte encoding may be non-default
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; Closer examination of the code reveals that the comment is right - the
&gt;&gt;&gt; encoding is downright ignored for single-byte encodings... this can be
&gt;&gt;&gt; seen immediately by the fact that the encoding argument is not passed
&gt;&gt;&gt; down to further methods in the chain.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; So the stream of bytes is not correctly converted to a char (actual
&gt;&gt;&gt; conversion appears in the charAt method of ByteReplayCharSequence):
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; return (char)(c & 0xff);
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; where c is an int. I guess this formula is correct only for ISO-8859-1.
&gt;&gt;&gt;     
&gt;&gt; This is definitely a problem; I&#39;ve created a new bug:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;    http://webteam.archive.org/jira/browse/HER-1506
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; I think it&#39;s gone unnoticed for a while because:
&gt;&gt;   - this masking won&#39;t hurt single-byte characters &lt;= 0x7F
&gt;&gt;   - prevalent single-byte encodings are very similar in this range 
&gt;&gt; inherited from ASCII
&gt;&gt;   - our usual configurations only use the ReplayCharSequence for link 
&gt;&gt; extraction, and link delimiters and link characters are often limited to 
&gt;&gt; ASCII, even when other content on the page varies
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; Maybe this could be easily fixed by a patch, but currently this
&gt;&gt;&gt; clearly means only ISO-8859-1 is supported as a single byte encoding (
&gt;&gt;&gt; I did not look much at multibyte encoding support but hope it is
&gt;&gt;&gt; better).
&gt;&gt;&gt;     
&gt;&gt; Actually, it&#39;s a little worse than that: only bytes &lt;=0x7F are read 
&gt;&gt; properly from a (Single)ByteReplayCharSequence.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; As getting back the actual bytes is also quite difficult, the priority
&gt;&gt;&gt; of this fix should be high IMHO.
&gt;&gt;&gt;     
&gt;&gt; It&#39;s actually quite easy to get the raw bytes: use the 
&gt;&gt; RecordingOutputStream.getReplayInputStream method (or 
&gt;&gt; getContentReplayInputStream to skip the HTTP headers). That will give a 
&gt;&gt; raw byte stream of the recorded fetched content.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; - Gordon @ IA
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; Jean-Noel
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; On Mon, Jun 2, 2008 at 11:36 PM, Gordon Mohr &lt;gojomo@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt;&gt;     
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Jean-Noël Rivasseau wrote:
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Hello,
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I had a problem with encoding today and took a look at Heritrix code.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Unfortunately it seems to me (from my understanding of the code) that
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Heritrix supports only ISO-8859-1 pages and UTF-8 pages. I have a page
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; encoded in windows-1252, and Heritrix is not able to read it
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; correctly.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Is better encoding support planned in the reasonable near future? This
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; seems not a totally trivial thing to do (else I coul have tried) as
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; the code is rather low level (ReplayCharSequence is probably the place
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; that would need to be fixed) and I am not sure how to proceed.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;         
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Heritrix should already support many other encodings -- limited mainly
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; by what support is in your Java VM.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; As per HTTP/1.1, when no other charset is specified, ISO-8859-1 is
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; assumed. See:
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec3.html#sec3.7.1
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Can you be more specific about the problem you encountered? What did
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Heritrix not read that you tried?
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; - Gordon @ IA
